>Personal note.
>     I had a good friend discover his bus was on fire while he was stopped 
>at
>a light.  Turns out the auxillary blower shorted and started to melt wires,
>which then ignited spilled oil around the filler tube.  No major damage or
>explosions, but his AFM and most of his engine wiring harness were
>destroyed....  I can only image what would happen if the fire had burned 
>for
>much longer.  Which is why everyone should carry a fire extinguisher in
>their bus.  I keep mine in the slot under the drivers seat(always close at
>hand and usually"hopefully" far from the fire.  Another point to make about
>fire safety is to keep your fuel ring up off the tin surface.  Of course
>this relates to my 78 transporter and YMMV.  Maybe there is a flame
>retardant coating that could be applied to high pressure fuel lines that
>could delay tragedy.  Any thoughts??
>
>Isaiah Smith
>78 Champy the Wunderbus
